Basic Git Commands:



Cloning a repository:
-> git clone (HTTPS LINK)



Checking changes:
-> git status



Update changes and prepares for next commit:
-> git add --all OR git add -A
	updates everything

-> git add .
	updates only the files in the current directory

-> git add *
	updates only new or modified files, but not deleted files

-> git add *.txt, add *.exe, etc.
	updates all .txt/.exe etc. files within the current directory



Commit changes:
-> git commit -m "..."
	commits all changes adding "..." within the updated contents
 
-> git reset HEAD~
	undoes all changes made with the last commit



Delete files:
-> git rm "..."
	removes the named file

-> git rm -f "..."
	removes named file regardless of committed changes

-> git rm --cached "..."
	only removes it from staging (keeps the file in local directory)

-> git rm -r "..."
	-r means recursive, meaning any other folders/contents within the item removed will also be removed



Viewing commits:
-> git log
	shows details regarding last commits



Branching:
(Creates a "test" environment that copies the files from your main branch that allows you to test using main files)
-> git branch 
	shows all branches

-> git branch "..."
	creates a new branch

-> git checkout "..."
	enters the branch specified

-> git merge (branch name) -m "..."
	merges the current branch with the main branch with the ... text










-> To undo the last change; -> git reset
-> To undo manually deleted files; -> git reset --hard




